President Jacob Zuma finally delivered his State of the Nation Address, concentrating on the economy, wage talks, Eskom and the national minimum wage. CAPE TOWN - President Jacob Zuma finally delivered his State of the Nation Address, concentrating on the economy, wage talks, Eskom and the national minimum wage, saying that there needs to be radical social economic transformation.Zuma says there needs to be radical change.&quot;We need fundamental change in the structure, systems, institutions and patterns of ownership, management and control of the economy.&quot;He says white households are earning far more than their black counterparts.Added to this, ownership needs to be corrected with the JSE an example of white dominance.&quot;In terms of the 2015-16 information submitted to the Employment Equity Commission, the representation of whites at top management level amounted to 72%, whilst African representation was at 10%.&quot;He says that better economic growth is expected this year.&quot;Indications are that we have entered a period of recovery. We anticipate an economic growth rate of 1.3% in 2017.&quot;The president says that the minimum wage will also help many households.&quot;We congratulate the deputy president and Nedlac for this milestone and wish them well for work that still needs to be done.&quot;He added that the drive to stop water leaks had led to job creation.&quot;About 10,000 unemployed youth are being trained plumbers, artisans and water agents. More will be recruited this year to reach the total of 15,000.&quot;He then turned to the Esidimeni tragedy where 94 patients died.&quot;Compatriots we are deeply distressed by the deaths of so many psychiatric patients in Gauteng.&quot;Zuma says plans are underway to make sure this didn't happen again.&quot;We welcome the recommendation of the Health Ombudsman that there is an urgent need to review the National Health Act and the Mental Health Act with a view that certain powers and functions revert back to the Minister of Health.&quot;WATCH: Another chaotic Sona as the EFF is ejected from ParliamentEarlier, proceedings got off to a turbulent start with EFF leader Julius Malema clashing with National Assembly Speaker Baleka Mbete, saying that President Jacob Zuma needed to leave the house.Mbete then ordered Malema to leave.&quot;Honourable Malema, please leave the House. May I ask the sergeant-at-arms to please escort Honourable Malema out of the House.His party members were also ordered to leave and when they refused, security personnel were called in.Punches and water bottles were thrown as EFF MPs and security personnel clashed before the MPs were removed.WATCH: 'Rotten to the core!' - Malema in fighting mode at Sona 2017Before President Zuma could begin his address, Democratic Alliance MPs walked out of Parliament.Party leader Mmusi Maimane criticised the use of the military and slammed Zuma.&quot;The president has broken the law. This Parliament does not stand and we cannot stand for a violation of the Constitution.&quot;The Democratic Alliance then left.The Freedom Front Plus and Cope MPs followed suit by walking out of Parliament.ANC secretary-general Gwede Mantashe has suggested that National Assembly Speak Baleka Mbete was too patient with Economic Freedom Fighters MPs and their attempts to delay President Jacob Zuma from delivering his State of the Nation Address.&quot;If I was the Speaker, I would not have let this things go on for an hour. If people have come to Parliament with the intention of disrupting, the Speaker should have dealt with it quicker,&quot; Mantashe said after the State of the Nation Address.WATCH: F#ck you! Sona 2017 descends into chaotic screaming matchFollowing his party's ejection from the National Assembly, EFF leader Julius Malema has vowed to continue to hold President Jacob Zuma accountable whenever he is in Parliament.Malema says Zuma has broken his oath of office, therefore he cannot address Members of Parliament.&quot;We are not going to be intimidated by soldiers, by police or criminals who are hell bent at defending a constitutional delinquent a man who is prepared to violate the Constitution. They are ready to chase out people who break the rules of Parliament but prepared to defend a man who broke his oath of office.&quot;